@model FinanceApp.Models.ViewModels.LoginViewModel

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Login";
}

<h2 class="text-center mb-3">@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
@Html.ValidationSummary(true, "", new { @class = "text-danger" })

<form asp-action="Login" method="post">
    @Html.AntiForgeryToken()
    <div class="mb-3">
        <label asp-for="Email" class="form-label"></label>
        <input asp-for="Email" class="form-control" />
        <span asp-validation-for="Email" class="text-danger"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-3">
        <label asp-for="Password" class="form-label"></label>
        <input asp-for="Password" class="form-control" />
        <span asp-validation-for="Password" class="text-danger"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="form-check mb-3">
        <input asp-for="RememberMe" class="form-check-input" />
        <label asp-for="RememberMe" class="form-check-label"></label>
    </div>
    <div class="text-center my-3">
        <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Login</button>
    </div>
</form>

@section Scripts {
    <partial name="_ValidationScriptsPartial" />
}
@*this is an ASP.NET Core Razor view (Razor Pages / MVC view) for a 
    login form. I’ll walk through it top-to-bottom and explain 
    what each piece does and why it’s there.

What this file does (short)

It renders a Bootstrap-styled login form that is strongly typed 
to a LoginViewModel. It shows validation messages, includes an 
anti-forgery token for CSRF protection, and posts the form to 
an action named Login.

Line-by-line / block explanation

@model FinanceApp.Models.ViewModels.LoginViewModel
Declares the view’s model type. That makes Razor helpers and tag 
helpers strongly typed (e.g., asp-for="Email" is bound to LoginViewModel.Email).

@{ ViewData["Title"] = "Login"; }
Sets the page title (useful for layout pages that render ViewData["Title"]).

<h2 class="text-center mb-3">@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
A Bootstrap-styled heading centered with some margin-bottom.

@Html.ValidationSummary(true, "", new { @class = "text-danger" })
Shows a validation summary. The parameters mean:

true = exclude property-level errors (so this shows only 
model-level errors, not the field-specific ones). Property 
errors are displayed next to individual fields with asp-validation-for.

"" = no custom summary message.

new { @class = "text-danger" } = adds the CSS class (red text).

<form asp-action="Login" method="post">
A form using the Tag Helpers (asp-action) that will post to the 
Login action on the current controller. method="post" means HTTP POST.

@Html.AntiForgeryToken()
Adds a hidden anti-forgery token input to protect against CSRF 
attacks. On the server, you should validate it (commonly with 
[ValidateAntiForgeryToken] or with automatic validation).

Field blocks (example for Email and Password)

<div class="mb-3">
    <label asp-for="Email" class="form-label"></label>
    <input asp-for="Email" class="form-control" />
    <span asp-validation-for="Email" class="text-danger"></span>
</div>


label asp-for="Email" emits a <label> whose text comes from 
    the model metadata (property name or [Display(Name = "...")]).

input asp-for="Email" emits an <input> with id, name and value 
bound to the Email property. The Tag Helper chooses input 
attributes based on model metadata (for example, if the model 
property has [DataType(DataType.EmailAddress)] it may set type="email").

span asp-validation-for="Email" is where the field-specific 
validation message will appear (client + server).

form-check block for RememberMe (checkbox)

input asp-for="RememberMe" class="form-check-input" renders 
a checkbox tied to the RememberMe boolean property.

label asp-for="RememberMe" class="form-check-label" renders the 
label for the checkbox. Bootstrap’s form-check classes arrange 
the checkbox + label.

Submit button

<div class="text-center my-3">
    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary">Login</button>
</div>


Simple Bootstrap-styled submit button, centered.

@section Scripts { <partial name="_ValidationScriptsPartial" /> }
Includes client-side validation scripts (usually jQuery Validate + 
unobtrusive validation) via the _ValidationScriptsPartial partial. 
This enables client-side validation if you have the necessary 
script bundle in your layout.

How the flow works (server side)

User loads this view (GET). If LoginViewModel has default values, 
inputs will be prefilled.

User fills fields and submits — the browser sends a POST to the Login action.

In the controller action you typically accept LoginViewModel model 
and check ModelState.IsValid. If invalid, return View(model) to 
redisplay with validation messages.

If valid, perform authentication (check credentials), sign-in, redirect, etc.

Example controller action:

[HttpPost]
[ValidateAntiForgeryToken]
public IActionResult Login(LoginViewModel model)
{
    if (!ModelState.IsValid) return View(model);
    // authenticate user...
    return RedirectToAction("Index", "Home");
}

Small notes / recommendations

Password input type: Tag Helper will set input type depending on 
model metadata. If your Password property doesn’t have 
[DataType(DataType.Password)], the rendered <input> might be type="text". 
To ensure it's masked, either:

Add [DataType(DataType.Password)] to the Password property, or

explicitly set type="password":
<input asp-for="Password" type="password" class="form-control" />

ValidationSummary(true, ...) is good when you want field-level 
messages next to fields and only show overall model errors 
(e.g., "Invalid login attempt") in the summary.

Keep @Html.AntiForgeryToken() and [ValidateAntiForgeryToken] 
on the action to protect from CSRF.

If posting to a different controller, add asp-controller="Account" on the <form>.*@